<h1>5.4 Order of adjective and noun</h1>
<p><strong>In progress</strong></p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes-syntactic-relation-labels">Relevant postag
codes / syntactic relation labels</h2>
<p><strong>Position in postag string</strong>: 1st (part of speech)</p>
<p><strong>Letters</strong>: a (adjective), n (noun)</p>
<p><strong>Syntactic label</strong>: An attributive adjective is
annotated with the ATR label (ATR_CO if in coordination).</p>
<p><strong>Example</strong>: τὰ ἀρσενικὰ ἱερεῖα<br>
tà arsenikà hiereîa<br>
<em>the male sacrificial animals</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/24080">P.cair.zen.2.59152</a>, 5-6
(sent. 2)</p>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""></div><p></p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary:</h2>
<p>For proper adjectives, in indefinite NPs both orders -
<em>noun-adjective</em> and <em>adjective-noun</em> - are attested, the
preference for one or the other likely driven by pragmatic reasons. In
definite NPs, the most common position of the adjective is internal,
i.e.&nbsp;between the article and the noun; when the adjective is not
internal, in papyri it is much more often placed after the noun than
before it. Quantifiers are predominantly placed before the noun,</p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion:</h2>
<p>Traditionally, the grammars of Ancient Greek discuss the position of
the modifier in the noun phrase mostly in terms of its position with
respect to the article, differentiating between attributive and
predicative position in <em>definite NPs</em> (cf. <span class="citation" data-cites="emde2019">Emde Boas et al. (2019)</span>).
An adjective in attributive position, i.e.&nbsp;preceded directly by the
article, describes the referent’s attribute, characteristic, origin,
possessor, target, etc.:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>τὴν <strong>ταλαίπωρον</strong> θυγατέρα<br>
tḕn talaípōron thugatéra<br>
<em>the miserable daughter</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/27163">p.fouad.75</a>, 4-5, sent.
2.</p></li>
<li><p>τὸ συνθεσείδιον τὸ <strong>λευκόν</strong><br>
tò suntheseídion tò leukón<br>
<em>the white dress</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/27741">p.giss.apoll.1</a>, 8-9,
sent. 4.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>An adjective in predicative position, i.e.&nbsp;not preceded by the
article, provides no identifying description of the referent, but gives
information about its condition:</p>
<ol start="3" type="1">
<li><strong>ὀψίας</strong> τῆς ὥρας (ἀπελθοῦσα)<br>
opsías tês hṓras (apelthoúsa) <em>(having left) in the late
hour</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1278">bgu.2.380</a>, 3,sent. 2.</li>
<li>τῷ υἱῷ [μου] <strong>[ὀρ]φ̣α̣ν̣ῷ̣</strong><br>
tôi huiôi mou <strong>orphanôi</strong><br>
<em>to my orphaned son</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/22323">p.babatha.15</a>, 5, sent.
3</li>
</ol>
<p>In the treebanking framework adopted by the PapyGreek project <span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014c">(Celano 2014c)</span>,
attributive adjectives are always annotated as ATR (ATR_CO). Modifiers
in predicative position are annotated according to their function:
ADV/ADV_CO if functioning as adjuncts, and PNOM/PNOM_CO if used as
predicative complements, and ATR/ATR_CO if they cannot be qualified as
either, but rather modify the noun closely. The discussion below
concerns attributive adjectives and those adjectives in predicative
position that have been deemend by the annotator to be neither adjuncts
nor predicative complements.</p>
<p>Additionally, in the AGDT treebanking framework there is no
distinction made between adjectives, demonstratives, and quantifiers,
all receiving the morphological annotation of <em>adjectives</em>.
Within the PapyGreek project, we have chosen to annotate demonstrative
adjectives morphologically as pronouns due to their pronominal origin.
They are therefore discussed in chapter <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/96">5.6. Order of demonstrative and
noun</a>. For differentiating between quantifiers and proper adjectives,
additional annotation has been performed outside of the scope of the
PapyGreek treebanking framework (Yordanova-Nanev, forthcoming).</p>
<p>The modern scholarly consensus (<span class="citation" data-cites="dik1997">Dik (1997)</span>, <span class="citation" data-cites="emde2019">Emde Boas et al. (2019)</span>) is that, in
Classical Greek, the main factor behind the preferred ordering is
pragmatics: the “natural”, unmarked order is the noun preceding the
adjective, while an adjective preceding its governing noun is emphasized
in some way. However, there are other factors that can influence the
position of the adjectival modifier in the noun phrase, like the
semantic type of the adjective (<span class="citation" data-cites="bergson1960">Bergson (1960)</span>, <span class="citation" data-cites="devinestephens2000">Devine and Stephens (2000)</span>).</p>
<p>In papyri, articular phrases show similar frequencies of the order
patterns to those attested in the treebanked literary corpus, where the
most common placement of the adjective is between the article and the
noun. In indefinite phrases, the smaller size of our corpus increases
the relevance of the instances of individual lemmas with high frequency.
Therefore, in PapyGreek adjectives appear more often after the noun,
which is in contrast to what is observed in literary materials, where
the ratio is inverted. However, the prevalence of postposed adjectives
over preposed ones in papyri is confirmed through investigation of the
larger automatically annotated Duke-nlp corpus.</p>
<p>Quantifiers are predominantly placed in a prenominal position.</p>
